{"runId":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash@2026-05-13T21-10-29-024Z","slug":"one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams","locale":"hi","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","modelPath":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash","createdAt":"2026-05-13T21:12:20.607Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/hi/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/hi/deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash/2026-05-13T21-10-29-024Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"5e23bd6661ed61df952a39bf65d61ca0a0d01f23e047cdf168f7bbdac407baeb","outputHash":"677091c3acddaa4993f14f8cd84c73a47a326925dd3d49058be55b414aa6fbc1","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that feature teams can accelerate early development by starting with a simple key-value (KV) store (e.g., Redis, S3) instead of immediately choosing SQL or MongoDB. It frames this as a \"neat trick\" to avoid schema churn and migration costs, noting that KV patterns are already familiar (e.g., URLs, configs) and can represent graphs or trees. The tutorial-style piece advises using KV when data is accessed by unique key and scaling is needed, but warns against it for JOINs, property searches, or unbounded datasets. It emphasizes that migrating from KV to SQL is easier than the reverse, and that starting with KV forces clearer thinking about data requirements.","totalInputTokens":6495,"totalOutputTokens":10681,"totalCacheReadTokens":768,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":53565,"totalCostUsd":0.0037946104000000005,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","chunkSize":"10p","totalChunks":5,"totalInputTokens":6495,"totalOutputTokens":10681,"totalCacheReadTokens":768,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":53565,"totalCostUsd":0.0037946104000000005,"pricingSource":